	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Jamaican agricultural trade policy reviewed under WTO TPR process</h1>

			
			<h4>
												03 April 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to the WTO Secretariat’s latest trade policy review of the country, Jamaica remains ‘a net importer of agricultural products’ with agricultural imports more than three times the level of exports in 2008. The contribution of agriculture to GDP has been in steady decline and now accounts for only 5%. According to the WTO Secretariat, periodic natural disasters (hurricanes in 2004, 2005, 2007 and 2008) have led to serious decline in the agricultural sector. Labour productivity has also been in decline, partly as a result of the small average size of land holdings (less than one hectare).</p><p>Nevertheless, the agriculture sector remains an important contributor to employment (around 20% of the total labour force in 2009) and export earnings, mainly from sugar, coffee and citrus, and, until 2008, bananas.</p><a name="eztoc434595_0_0_0_0_1" id="eztoc434595_0_0_0_0_1"></a><h6>Export volume of traditional crops, 2004‑08 (in tonnes)</h6><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
<tr>
<td width="102" valign="top">  <b>&nbsp;</b>
