</table>
<p>Source: Planning Institute of Jamaica (2009), Final Draft Agricultural Sector Plan, p.6, September.</p><p>The sugar sector provides around 35,000 jobs, but has extremely high costs (US$0.20-0.23 per pound produced). With the progressive reduction of guaranteed prices on the EU market, this is posing a serious challenge. The government’s response has been to privatise the industry, with the aim of creating ‘a sustainable private-sector-led sugar cane industry’. According to a recent statement by Jamaica’s agriculture minister, Christopher Tufton, the government seeks to promote a sugar sector focused on ‘value-added businesses’ within the sugar chain. With a view to achieving more economical levels of sugar-cane production as a foundation for such value-added processing activities, the Jamaican government has launched a drive to increase the land under sugar cane by bringing unutilised land into production.</p><p>Currently, according to the WTO Secretariat, all imports and exports of sugar take place through the Sugar Industry Authority (SIA). The SIA also determines individual factor production quotas as the need arises, and arbitrates in disputes between industry stakeholders.</p><p>In the banana sector, given the frequency of natural disasters in 2008, the Jamaica Producers’ Group, the main banana exporter, decided to end exports of bananas to the EU, and no bananas have been exported there since August 2008. In 2009, a draft banana/plantain policy was developed that focused on increasing production and productivity for local consumption and processing. The policy seeks to set the framework for all aspects of the banana industry: regulation, marketing, processing and consumption, and relations between stakeholders. The Banana Board currently exports directly and grants export permits to companies.</p><p>A statutory body, the Coffee Industry Board, regulates the coffee industry in Jamaica. It is the main exporter of Jamaican coffee, including the premium brand ‘Blue Mountain Coffee’. A policy of trade-mark registration is being pursued to try to secure the full commercial value of this quality-differentiated brand.</p><p>A similar Cocoa Industry Board regulates the cocoa sector, carrying the main responsibility for exports to Europe, the US and Japan. However, Jamaican cocoa exports declined 86% between 1996 and 2006, from 1,407 tonnes to 204 tonnes. This was partly a result of hurricane damage, and partly a result of low global prices. This has created a situation of limited investment and deteriorating yields in cocoa-growing areas.</p><p>At the policy level, the government’s 2009 Agriculture Sector Plan ‘seeks to reposition the sector for sustainable growth and development’, in view of the role of agriculture in long-term rural development and food security. Initiatives are under way to ‘improve production and productivity through the use of new technologies’ and through improvement of extension delivery, marketing and business development. Some 1.1% of the government budget was allocated to agriculture between 2003/04 and 2007/08.</p><p>In terms of agricultural trade policy, the government has moved from a protectionist approach based on import licences, reference prices, stamp duties and quantitative restrictions, towards a more liberalised agricultural trading environment. According to the WTO Secretariat, ‘most protectionist measures were either removed or converted to a simple <i>ad valorem</i>&nbsp;tariff’.</p><p>Tariff rates for agricultural products range from 0 to 100%, with an average of 19%. This, however, excludes the various stamp duties applied which, when taken into account, raise the average level of protection to 30.4%. Imports of agricultural produce are subject to licensing and compulsory inspection by the relevant government departments. Jamaica does not use export subsidies, but does provide export incentives to agri-industrial products (but not to unprocessed agricultural products). Jamaica has notified its domestic support measures to the WTO (with a total value in 2006/07 of US$18.5 million). Tax relief is also offered to all agricultural activities.</p><p>In terms of international agricultural trade relations, while subject to a process of erosion of their value, traditional trade preferences on the EU market have been preserved and partially extended under the CARIFORUM-EU EPA. A trade agreement with Canada is also under negotiation which it is hoped will open up new export opportunities. The WTO Secretariat report points out however that ‘a significant improvement in the level of competitiveness is needed in order to reverse the declining trends in the balance of trade’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
WTO, ‘Jamaica: Trade Policy Review’, point of access for full report from the WTO Secretariat and the government of Jamaica’s response, 7 December 2010<br/>

<a href="http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp342_e.htm" target="_self">http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/tpr_e/tp342_e.htm</a><br/>
Planning Institute of Jamaica, ‘Final Draft Agricultural Sector Plan’, p.6, September 2009. <br/>
<a href="http://www.vision2030.gov.jm/SectorPlans/tabid/75/Default.aspx" target="_self">http://www.vision2030.gov.jm/SectorPlans/tabid/75/Default.aspx</a>&nbsp;</p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Reorientation of economies and deep reform of the agriculture sector in particular were an expected consequence for a range of ACP states following the ongoing reform of the EU market for traditional exports such as sugar and bananas. This shift is clearly reflected in the WTO TPR of Jamaica. These economic challenges have been exacerbated by the global economic downturn and the frequent natural disasters that have hit Jamaica in recent years.</p><p>It is notable that Jamaica has sought to reform its sugar industry through government divestment and regulatory reform to match the new ownership structure. The same holds true for the banana industry. In addition, a notable reorientation of production towards serving domestic markets, linked to an expansion of the production of value-added products, is under way. This may require a certain level of public-sector support to pump-prime investments in innovation, similar to the assistance extended under the EU’s internal axis-1 rural development programmes.</p><p>While this process of restructuring is in progress, a contraction of employment and earnings is likely, and this will also require some level of public-sector intervention, if short-term political costs are not to derail longer-term restructuring efforts. It is in this context of fundamental restructuring that the industry-specific support offered by the EU can be very helpful. ‘The ‘aid for trade’ initiative could also be targeted to assist developing countries in facing these huge challenges, with governments, wherever possible, using ‘aid for trade’ funds to pump prime proactive adjustment processes.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
